[normal]Written evidence submitted by [bold]Government[bold] [bold]Departments [bold](CLC047)[bold]Executive Summary
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Introduction
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question 1: What is the current state of public understanding of what is meant by climate change? How has this changed in recent years? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question 2: Which voices are trusted in public discourse on climate science and policy? What role should Government Departments, scientific advisers to Government and publicly funded scientists have in communicating climate science?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question 3: How could public understanding of what is meant by climate change be improved? What are the main barriers to this? Does the media have a positive role to play?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question 4: 
[normal]How important is public understanding in developing effective climate change policy?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question 5: What evidence is there that public attitude to climate science affects their engagement with energy policies or initiatives?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question 6: Does the Government have sufficient expertise in social and behavioural sciences to understand the relationship between public understanding of climate science and the feasibility of relevant public policies?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Question 7: 
[normal]Can lessons about public engagement with climate change policy be learned from other countries?
[normal]&#xa0;
